<subSubSection id="C3136AEB5748FFACFF585889FC3F226A" pageId="15" pageNumber="446" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="8BB639605748FFACFF585889FACD2395" blockId="15.[151,1437,561,804]" box="[199,1402,705,732]" pageId="15" pageNumber="446">
<emphasis id="B97DE5725748FFACFF585889FED62392" bold="true" box="[199,353,705,731]" pageId="15" pageNumber="446">Distribution.</emphasis>
Only known from 
<typeStatus id="54B287C25748FFACFDA8588AFDD02395" box="[567,615,706,732]" pageId="15" pageNumber="446">type</typeStatus>
locality in 
<collectingCountry id="F31E79F05748FFACFD795889FC8F2392" box="[742,824,705,731]" name="Bolivia" pageId="15" pageNumber="446">Bolivia</collectingCountry>
[
<collectingRegion id="49CDF7825748FFACFCD95889FC7D2395" box="[838,970,705,732]" country="Bolivia" name="Santa Cruz" pageId="15" pageNumber="446">Santa Cruz</collectingRegion>
]; see 
<bibRefCitation id="EF9844915748FFACFB98588AFABD2392" author="Perger, R. &amp; Rubio, G. D." box="[1031,1290,705,732]" pageId="15" pageNumber="446" pagination="0190582" refId="ref17655" refString="Perger, R. &amp; Rubio, G. D. (2018) A wolf in sheep's clothing: The description of a fly resembling jumping spider of the genus Scoturius Simon, 1901 (Araneae: Salticidae: Huriini). PLoS One, 13 (1), e 0190582. https: // doi. org / 10.1371 / journal. pone. 0190582" type="journal article" year="2018">Perger &amp; Rubio (2018)</bibRefCitation>
(
<figureCitation id="133225E55748FFACFA865889FADA2395" box="[1305,1389,705,732]" captionStart="FIGURES 77–78" captionStartId="22.[151,264,1761,1785]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,453,1729]" captionTargetId="figure-127@22.[151,1436,453,1738]" captionTargetPageId="22" captionText="FIGURES 77–78. Regionalization in Neotropical view (Morrone 2014) and distributional records for huriine jumping spiders (records of Urupuyu not included). 77 Neotropical, South America, Brazilian subregion Chacoan subregion, South America Transition Zone, Andean Region. 78 Southern of South America, Brazil, Uruguay, Argentina focusing on the distribution of Guriurius." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6417712" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6417712/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="446">Fig. 77</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BB639605748FFACFF5858ADFC3F226A" blockId="15.[151,1437,561,804]" pageId="15" pageNumber="446">
<emphasis id="B97DE5725748FFACFF5858ADFE3423B6" bold="true" box="[199,387,741,767]" pageId="15" pageNumber="446">Natural history</emphasis>
. According to 
<bibRefCitation id="EF9844915748FFACFDAC58AEFCF523B6" author="Perger, R. &amp; Rubio, G. D." box="[563,834,741,768]" pageId="15" pageNumber="446" pagination="0190582" refId="ref17655" refString="Perger, R. &amp; Rubio, G. D. (2018) A wolf in sheep's clothing: The description of a fly resembling jumping spider of the genus Scoturius Simon, 1901 (Araneae: Salticidae: Huriini). PLoS One, 13 (1), e 0190582. https: // doi. org / 10.1371 / journal. pone. 0190582" type="journal article" year="2018">Perger &amp; Rubio (2018)</bibRefCitation>
, this species was collected by beating tray and was suggested as a mimic of flies. Altitudinal distribution: 
<quantity id="4CF194855748FFACFD675941FC88226D" box="[760,831,777,804]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.8" pageId="15" pageNumber="446" unit="m" value="480.0">480 m</quantity>
a. s. l.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
